            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Santos-Miller is a product of two worlds. The son of a pragmatic Filipina nurse from Cebu and a free-spirited carpenter from Oregon, he grew up in Daly City, feeling the constant, gentle pull between his mother\u2019s emphasis on stability and his father\u2019s belief in working with your hands. He was never a stellar student in the traditional sense; the classroom felt confining. His true education happened outside, sketching in notebooks and watching graffiti artists transform bleak concrete walls into vibrant murals.\n\nHis path diverged sharply from his peers after high school. While they left for college, Marco stayed home. His father\u2019s health had declined, and taking on work as a handyman and later a barista was a necessity, a quiet act of familial duty he never questioned. During these years, he found his university in the alleyways of the Mission District, learning composition and color theory from the city itself. He began volunteering at a local youth center, teaching kids the basics of spray-can art, discovering a passion for mentorship that surprised even him.\n\nThis volunteer work became his lifeline, leading to his current position as a Program Assistant at a non-profit offering free arts education. Now 38, Marco lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Mission with his long-term partner, Chloe, a graphic designer. His daily 2.8-mile bike commute to their SOMA office is a moving meditation, a chance to observe the city\u2019s shifting light and textures. His $62,000 salary requires a careful budget, but his life feels rich with purpose.\n\nMarco\u2019s greatest hope is to one day run the program he now assists. He dreams of securing a major grant to create a multi-story mural celebrating the neighborhood\u2019s immigrant history, a permanent testament to the communities often overlooked in the city\u2019s glittering tech narrative. He carries a quiet anxiety about being priced out of the city he loves, but he channels that fear into his work, believing deeply that nurturing the creativity of the next generation is the surest way to protect San Francisco's soul."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 14, helping his dad build a simple bookshelf in their Daly City garage. He remembers the specific scent of sawdust and the patient way his father showed him how to measure, how to feel the grain of the wood. When they finished, his dad ran a hand over the smooth pine and nodded, a look of quiet pride on his face. In that moment, Marco understood the deep satisfaction of creating something tangible and useful\u2014a lesson that cemented his belief in the value of working with your hands.\n\n2.\nAt 16, feeling lost and bored with school, he cut through Clarion Alley on a foggy afternoon and stopped dead. A mural of colossal, vibrant figures seemed to burst from the concrete, telling a story in a language he understood better than any textbook. The classroom felt gray, but this was alive. It was a defiant shout of color, a public and powerful act of creation. He knew then that art wasn't just for museums; it was for the streets, and he had to learn that language.\n\n3.\nHe was 22, coming home exhausted after a double shift at the cafe to the quiet hum of his mother\u2019s prayers for his sick father. The weight of responsibility felt crushing. Instead of sleeping, he\u2019d go to his room and sketch for hours, the scratching of pencil on paper a way to process a life that felt too adult. Art stopped being just a passion and became a necessity\u2014an anchor in the overwhelming tide of duty, the only space that was truly his own.\n\n4.\nHe was 27, volunteering at the youth center. A shy kid named Leo had been struggling, his spray-can control shaky. Marco showed him a simple trick for fading colors, his hand gently guiding his. When Leo stepped back to look at the fierce, beautiful wolf he\u2019d created, his face lit up with a grin that could power the city. In Leo\u2019s pride, Marco felt a jolt of purpose far stronger than finishing his own piece. He wasn\u2019t just teaching art; he was helping someone find their voice.\n\n5.\nAge 30. He remembers the day he and Chloe got the keys to their Inner Mission apartment. It was small, the rent a stretch, but it was theirs. Standing at the window, watching the evening light hit the buildings across the street, he felt an overwhelming sense of relief. They had found a foothold in a city that always felt like it was trying to shake them off. That feeling of shared victory against the odds became the foundation upon which he was determined to build his life."
